EDITORS COMMENTS

The print captures a significant moment in history as President Emile Loubet arrives in Algeria aboard the majestic cruiser "Jeanne d'Arc". The engraving, originally featured in the renowned French journal "Le Petit Parisien" on April 26,1903, showcases the grandeur of this arrival. As the boat docks at the harbor, President Loubet stands tall and dignified, representing not only France but also symbolizing hope for a prosperous future between Algeria and its colonial power. The image portrays a fusion of cultures - Arab civilization blending with French influence. The liner itself is an impressive sight to behold, reflecting both power and elegance. Its presence signifies the importance placed on this visit by President Loubet and his government. This event marked a turning point in Franco-Algerian relations during that era. This engraving by Leonard de Selva transports us back to a time when North Africa was still under colonial rule. It serves as a reminder of historical events that have shaped our world today. With its rich details and intricate craftsmanship, this print offers viewers an opportunity to delve into the past and explore various aspects of Algerian society at that time. From bustling harbors to diverse communities living side by side, it encapsulates both beauty and complexity within one frame. Preserved within private collections worldwide, this remarkable artwork continues to inspire curiosity about our shared history while highlighting the artistic talent of Leonard de Selva.
